Unit testing in R

Why test?

See the Testing chapter of Advanced R for a full discussion of why we should test our outputs, but to summarise:

  • Testing helps us discover bugs; we can’t fix what we don’t know isn’t broken.
  • Fewer bugs \(\approx\) greater confidence in our code and outputs
  • Ensure we don’t break something when we introduce new code
  • Prevent this just before publication:

Testing just before publication

What to test?

We should ideally test as much code output as is useful and possible. In a data analysis project, that will usually boil down to:

  • Data preparation scripts, and
  • Functions

We don’t need to test everything. Instead, prioritise functions and code blocks that are more complex, are more fragile, or that depend on or feed into other blocks of code. But, be careful not to assume the output of a block of code is obvious:

x <- 1:5
is.vector(x)
[1] TRUE
attr(x, "label") <- letters[1:5]
is.vector(x)
[1] FALSE

By way of explanation, is.vector() only returns TRUE if the object is a vector and has no attributes apart from names (http://adv-r.had.co.nz/Data-structures.html#vectors). This is definitely one to watch out for if you regularly import SPSS files and include the label attributes.

Data analysis scripts - testing inline

For data analysis scripts I recommend you add checks to your script as you go along. You’re probably already checking your results so it’s often just a case of writing the tests explicitly in your script rather than testing interactively. This also makes it easier to pick up code after a break.

It’s older code, sir, but it checks out

I find tests are most useful when I’m doing something that could change the data without me realising, such as:

  • Any joins or merges - ALWAYS check you have the right number of cases!
  • Where you change the type of an object, especially when going from character to numeric, or numeric to logical.
  • Where NAs might be introduced, such as a full_join(). assertthat::noNA() is useful for this.
  • When dealing with factors, especially with numbers as factor levels (is it 1.0, or is it factor level 1?).

The example tests here are relatively trivial, but are only designed to show you how to test, not what to test. Let’s load the packages we need and save some data to a temporary directory demonstrate. The data is very close to my heart and is available from the International Coffee Organization:

suppressMessages(library("tidyverse"))
library("stringr")
library("assertthat")

You can no doubt see a number of problems, but lets see if we can pick this up with testing. We can use base’s stopifnot() or the assertthat package for tests. Both do essentially the same thing, but you can add a customised error message with assertthat::assert_that() which is sometimes useful.

First I want to make sure there aren’t any blank rows:

assertthat::noNA(coffee$country)
[1] FALSE

On seeing this I would amend my script and, when re-run, hopefully the test will pass:

coffee <- 
  readxl::read_xlsx("inst/extdata/coffee.xlsx", skip = 3) %>% 
  rename(country = "Calendar years") %>% 
  select(country, `2013`) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(country))
assertthat::noNA(coffee$country)
[1] TRUE

Next, I know from opening the Excel file there are 34 countries with data, so lets check:

assertthat::are_equal(nrow(coffee), 34L)  # 'L' is for integer, obviously
[1] FALSE

This test fails because there are a number of observations that aren’t counties, such as the European Union, a Total, and the copyright information for the data. There’s also a ‘Belgium/Luxembourg’ row where the data for these countries was combined in earlier years. Lets remove these and re-test:

coffee <- 
  readxl::read_xlsx("inst/extdata/coffee.xlsx", skip = 3) %>% 
  rename(country = "Calendar years") %>% 
  select(country, `2013`) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(country)) %>% 
  filter(
    country != "European Union",
    country != "Total",
    !str_detect(country, "International Coffee Organization"),
    country != "Belgium/Luxembourg"
  )
assertthat::are_equal(nrow(coffee), 34L)
[1] TRUE

Another problem fixed. Now we have our script to prepare the data and our tests to make sure it’s working as intended. They should look something like this now:

coffee <- 
  readxl::read_xlsx("inst/extdata/coffee.xlsx", skip = 3) %>% 
  rename(country = "Calendar years") %>% 
  select(country, `2013`) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(country)) %>% 
  filter(
    country != "European Union",
    country != "Total",
    !str_detect(country, "International Coffee Organization"),
    country != "Belgium/Luxembourg"
  )
assertthat::noNA(coffee$country)
[1] TRUE
assertthat::noNA(coffee$`2013`)
[1] TRUE
assertthat::are_equal(nrow(coffee), 34L)
[1] TRUE

You are technically correct

One of the advantages of having specified our tests is that if we go back and change something in our script and accidentally break something, the tests will alert us. Imagine we accidentally remove one of the countries:

coffee <- coffee[1:33, ]  # oops, we meant 34 (or even better nrow(coffee)!)

Now the tests will fail alerting us to the issue:

assertthat::noNA(coffee$country)
[1] TRUE
assertthat::noNA(coffee$`2013`)
[1] TRUE
assertthat::are_equal(nrow(coffee), 34L)
[1] FALSE

The bug you fixed introduces a new bug

Testing functions

The other things you should test are functions. Functions are useful to perform the same procedure on multiple objects. Imagine we want to convert the units in our coffee table from its current ‘thousands of 60kg bags’ to simply kg. Ordinarily in R we’d just do this as a vector operation, but lets write a function to illustrate the point. Create the function in R/ which we can do automatically with usethis:

usethis::use_r("convert-unit")

The function itself should take a number, multiply it by 60, and multiply it by 1000:

convert_bags_kg <- function(bags) {
  kg = bags * 60 * 1000
  kg
}

You can load functions in R/ files with devtools::load_all().

devtools::load_all()
Loading RUnitTesting

Before we use the function, lets test it and make sure it produces the correct output. I would expect 50 units in the coffee table to be equivalent to (50 \(\times\) 60 \(\times\) 1000 \(=\)) 3,000,000kg. I would also expect that if the function encountered an NA it would return an NA (NA \(\times\) 60 \(\times\) 1000 \(=\) NA!) so I’m also going to explicitly test for this.

Add a test to the tests/ directory with:

usethis::use_test("convert_bags_kg")

And run the test with devtools::test():

devtools::test()
Loading RUnitTesting
Loading required package: testthat

Attaching package: ‘testthat’

The following object is masked from ‘package:dplyr’:

    matches

The following object is masked from ‘package:purrr’:

    is_null

Testing RUnitTesting

⠏ |  0       | test-convert_bags_kg.R
⠋ |  1       | test-convert_bags_kg.R
⠙ |  2       | test-convert_bags_kg.R
[32m✔[39m |  2       | test-convert_bags_kg.R[36m [0.1 s][39m

══ [1mResults[22m ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
[36mDuration: 0.3 s[39m

OK:       [32m2[39m
Failed:   [32m0[39m
Warnings: [32m0[39m
Skipped:  [32m0[39m

The output will tell you which (if any) tests fail and which pass.

Now we can confidently convert from thousands of 60kg bags to kg in the coffee data set:

coffee <- 
  readxl::read_xlsx("inst/extdata/coffee.xlsx", skip = 3) %>% 
  rename(country = "Calendar years") %>% 
  select(country, `2013`) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(country)) %>% 
  filter(
    country != "European Union",
    country != "Total",
    !str_detect(country, "International Coffee Organization"),
    country != "Belgium/Luxembourg"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(kg = convert_bags_kg(`2013`)) %>% 
  select(country, kg)
head(coffee)

That’s 6.9556810^{9}kg of coffee in 2013, or 2.523610^{8}kg in the UK, of which I myself drank 2.523610^{7}kg.

Again, the advantage of explicitly writing unit tests is that, if we modify the function and accidentally break its behaviour, the unit tests will alert us. Try it and see!

Coverage reports

If you’re testing using testthat in this way, you can easily run reports that indicate how much of your code is tested with automated tests. You can get a coverage report with covr:

covr::report()
